lated by the Malta Gaming Authority too. The Australian business is regulated and licensed by the [[Government of the Northern Territory|Northern Territory Government]]. In addition to the company headquarters in Stoke-on-Trent, Bet365 have further offices in Manchester, [[Gibraltar]], Malta, Bulgaria and Australia. In New Jersey, Bet365's gambling services is regulated by the [[New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement]].\n\nBet365 is a trading name of Hillside (New Media) Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASA Adjudication on Hillside (New Media) Ltd|url=https://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2014/2/Hillside-New-Media-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_245703.aspx#.VxzvpCMrKlN|work=|accessdate=24 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812072710/https://www.asa.org.uk/Rulings/Adjudications/2014/2/Hillside-New-Media-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_245703.aspx#.VxzvpCMrKlN|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and operations including payments through the affiliate programme<ref>{{cite web|title=bet365 affiliates terms and conditions|url=http://www.bet365affiliates.com/UI/Pages/Affiliates/?ContentPath=%2FAffiliates%2Fv2_Root%2FinformationPages%2FtermsAndConditions|work=|accessdate=22 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822011003/http://www.bet365affiliates.com/UI/Pages/Affiliates/?ContentPath=%2FAffiliates%2Fv2_Root%2FinformationPages%2FtermsAndConditions|archive-date=22 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> are carried out under that name.\n\nChairman [[Peter Coates]] also has the same position at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] and in May 2012 Bet365 signed a three-year contract with the club to become shirt sponsors.<ref>{{cite web|title=bet365 put their shirts on Stoke City|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-16022167-detail/story.html?|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=8 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618192318/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-16022167-detail/story.html|archive-date=18 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2016, the company became the new title sponsors for the [[Bet365 Stadium|club's stadium]] for the next six seasons, replacing fellow local enterprise the [[Britannia Building Society]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoke City's Britannia Stadium to be known as bet365 Stadium next season|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/apr/21/stoke-city-britannia-stadium-bet365-stadium|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604010225/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/apr/21/stoke-city-britannia-stadium-bet365-stadium|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the summer of 2016, Bet365 also signed shirt sponsorship deals with Bulgarian clubs [[Ludogorets Razgrad]] and [[PFC Slavia Sofia|Slavia Sofia]] for the upcoming two seasons.<ref>{{cite news|title=bet365 is the new general sponsor of Ludogorets|url=https://twitter.com/Ludogorets1945/status/745926027675897856|accessdate=31 July 2016|date=23 June 2016}}{{failed verification|date=October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBet365 was founded in 2000 in a portakabin<ref name=\"guardian\"/> in Stoke-on-Trent by [[Denise Coates]]. Denise developed a sports betting platform and trading team to launch the business online in March 2001. The business borrowed \u00a315 million from RBS against the family's betting shop estate which had been started by Peter Coates in 1974 and had been run by Denise Coates as managing director from 1995. Bet365 sold its betting shop chain in 2005 for \u00a340 million to [[Gala Coral Group|Coral]] and paid off its loan to RBS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |title=A Very Private Practice |accessdate=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406194952/http://www.egrmagazine.com/newsexclusive_a_very_private_practice |archivedate=6 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bet365 has grown into one of the world's largest online gambling companies with its reported figures to March 2018 showing amounts wagered on sports at \u00a352.56 billion, revenues of \u00a32.86 billion and an operating profit of \u00a3660.3 million.\n\nDenise Coates, joint chief executive, continues to run Bet365 and is the majority shareholder with 50.1% of the shares. Her brother [[John Coates (businessman)|John]], joint chief executive, runs the business alongside her, with her father Peter holding the position of chairman.\n\n==Awards and achievements==\nAt the eGaming Review Operator Awards 2010 organised by ''[[eGaming Review]]'' magazine, Bet365 won the \"Operator of the Year\" award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.egrmagazine.com/news/606887/bet365-wins-egr-operator-of-the-year-award.thtml|title=bet365 wins EGR Operator of the Year award|accessdate=29 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127203523/http://www.egrmagazine.com/news/606887/bet365-wins-egr-operator-of-the-year-award.thtml|archive-date=27 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bet365 ranked third in ''The Sunday Times Profit Track 100'' league table, which ranks private companies in the UK based on profit growth rate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=2&compID=1478&yr=2010 |title=Sunday Times Fast Track |accessdate=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331120805/http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=2&compID=1478&yr=2010 |archivedate=31 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bet365 was also ranked as one of the fastest growing privately owned technology, media and telecoms companies in ''[[The Sunday Times]] [[Tech Track 100]]'' league table.\n\n''eGaming Review'' magazine has ranked Bet365 the number one Internet gaming company in 2010, 2011 and 2012 as part of its annual Power 50 list of the top 50 most influential Internet gaming companies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.egrmagazine.com/news/exclusive_bet365_claims_power_50_crown_for_third_year_running |title=Exclusive: bet365 claims Power 50 crown for third year running |accessdate=18 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012021319/http://www.egrmagazine.com/news/exclusive_bet365_claims_power_50_crown_for_third_year_running |archive-date=12 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Denise Coates, founder and joint CEO of Bet365, received a CBE in the 2012 Queen's new year honours list for services to the community and business.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-16363002 |title= Denise Coates is among those named in New Year Honours |accessdate= 2 February 2012 |work= BBC News |date= 31 December 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120113053823/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-16363002 |archive-date= 13 January 2012 |url-status= live }}</ref> In February 2013 Denise Coates was named as one of the 100 most powerful women in the United Kingdom by ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' at [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01qj7jd/profiles/denise-coates | title=Denise Coates CBE | publisher=BBC | accessdate=7 May 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219082831/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01qj7jd/profiles/denise-coates | archive-date=19 February 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nAt the SBC Awards 2019, [https://sbcgaming.com/ SBC Gaming]awarded bet365 with \"Sportsbook of the Year\" accolade, for the sixth consecutive year. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/events/2019/12/04/sbc-awards-2019-sees-record-34-companies-enjoy-success/|title=SBC Awards 2019 Sees Record 34 Companies Enjoy Success|date=2019-12-04|website=SBC News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nIn October 2014, ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper reported that the company had been taking bets from Chinese citizens by using obscure domain names in order to avoid government web censorship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revealed: how Bet365 profits from Chinese punters who risk jail for gambling online|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/oct/03/bet365-profit-china-online-gambling|accessdate=2 June 2016|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531101158/http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/oct/03/bet365-profit-china-online-gambling|archive-date=31 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Bet365 were fined $2.75 million AUD for misleading advertisements which falsely promised \"free bets\" to customers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court imposes $2.75 million in penalties on bet365 companies for misrepresenting free bet offer|url=https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/court-imposes-275-million-in-penalties-on-bet365-companies-for-misrepresenting-free-bet-offer|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=Australian Competition & Consumer Commission|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042229/https://www.accc.gov.au/media-release/court-imposes-275-million-in-penalties-on-bet365-companies-for-misrepresenting-free-bet-offer|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDenise Coates became the highest paid executive in the UK in 2017, awarding herself a salary of \u00a3217m.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bet365 chief Denise Coates paid herself \u00a3217m last year|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/nov/12/bet365-chief-denise-coates-paid-217m-last-year|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126185631/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/nov/12/bet365-chief-denise-coates-paid-217m-last-year|archive-date=26 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, her pay packet rose to \u00a3265m as the company reported profits up 31% to \u00a3660m, prompting criticism from problem gambling charity groups.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chapman |first1=Ben |title=Bet365 boss Denise Coates' pay rises to 'eye-watering' \u00a3265m |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/bet365-denise-coates-boss-pay-265-million-pounds-salary-a8645351.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=5 January 2019 |language=en |date=21 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106010743/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/bet365-denise-coates-boss-pay-265-million-pounds-salary-a8645351.html |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In January 2019, Bet365 ranked second on ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' list of the UK\u2019s top taxpayers, with the Coates family \u2013 Denise, John and Peter \u2013 paying an estimated total tax of \u00a3156 million, of which \u00a399 million was paid by Denise alone.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK's 'highest taxpayers' revealed |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47015517 |website=BBC.com |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=27 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127082821/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47015517 |archive-date=27 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFurther criticism highlights repeated cases of Bet365 delaying or outright denying payment to winning players. For example, Bet365 was taken to court for refusing to pay over \u00a31&nbsp;million in winnings to a horse bettor in Northern Ireland in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusive: Teenager takes bet365 to court over \u00a31m 'won' on horse races|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/07/08/exclusive-teenager-takes-bet365-court-1m-won-horse-races/|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203141354/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/07/08/exclusive-teenager-takes-bet365-court-1m-won-horse-races/|archive-date=3 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The company refused a payout of \u00a354,000 to a punter in England in 2016, a case which is still ongoing as of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bet365 faces legal action over delay in paying winning punter \u00a354,000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/28/bet365-legal-action-delay-paying-punter-54000|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044556/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/28/bet365-legal-action-delay-paying-punter-54000|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bookmaker bet365 admits mistake in wrangle over \u00a354,000 account|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/apr/21/bet365-admits-error-frozen-account|accessdate=27 November 2017|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043844/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/apr/21/bet365-admits-error-frozen-account|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In Australia, Bet365 froze the account and refused to pay a punter who had won around $200,000 AUD in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Punter owed six-figure payout has account frozen after dog plunge|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/turf-thoroughbreds/punter-owed-sixfigure-payout-has-account-frozen-after-dog-plunge/news-story/ebd0d87e7fc0912fea042991b2a0e8cc|accessdate= 27 November 2017|work=The Australian}}</ref> These are just some of the most noteworthy instances; several more cases of Bet365 refusing to pay winnings have been reported by gamblers on Internet gambling forums.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://forumserver.twoplustwo.com/40/sports-betting/bet365-account-locked-5-months-ref-acsta-1502637/?highlight= |title=Bet365 Account Locked for 5 Months (ref. ACSTA)|website=TwoPlusTwo|access-date=27 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbookreview.com/forum/sportsbooks-industry/1047360-bet365-requests-strange-verification-way-secure-do-they-have-such-right.html|title=Bet365 requests strange verification way. Is it secure and do they have such right?|website=SporsBookReview|access-date=2 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044119/https://www.sportsbookreview.com/forum/sportsbooks-industry/1047360-bet365-requests-strange-verification-way-secure-do-they-have-such-right.html|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBet365 CEO [[Denise Coates]] is amongst the highest paid executives in UK. In 2018 she took home  \u00a3265 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casino.buzz/bet365-ceo-top-earning-executives-in-the-uk-with-323-million-pay-check/|title=Bet365 CEO Top Earning Executive In The Uk With \u00a3323 Million Pay Check|last=Ross|first=Cameri|date=2019-12-18|website=Casino.Buzz|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Stoke-on-Trent}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:Online gambling companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Gambling companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2000]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Online casinos]]\n[[Category:Coates family]]\n", "name_user": "Phil330d", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies:the content in the last sentence was already stated in the above paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bet365"}
{"title_page": "Vito (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Vito\n| caption        = \n| image          =\n| director       = [[Jeffrey Schwarz]]\n| producer       = Jeffrey Schwarz, [[Bryan Singer]]\n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Vito Russo]]\n| music          = [[Miriam Cutler]]\n| cinematography = David Quantic\n| editing        = Philip Harrison \n| distributor    = [[First Run Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2011|10|14|New York Film Festival}}\n| runtime        = 93 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Vito''''' is a 2011 American [[documentary film]] produced and directed by [[Jeffrey Schwarz]] of the [[Los Angeles]]-based production company [[Automat Pictures]]. The film documents the life of [[Vito Russo]], gay activist, film scholar, and author of ''[[The Celluloid Closet]]''.<ref name=Neil>{{cite news |last1=Genzlinger |first1=Neil |title='Vito,' a Documentary About Vito Russo, on HBO |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/23/arts/television/vito-a-documentary-about-vito-russo-on-hbo.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=22 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rooney |first1=David |title=Vito: Film Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/vito-film-review-248858 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=14 October 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n''Vito'' premiered at the 2011 [[New York Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Musto |first1=Michael |title=Vito Russo Documentary Makes The New York Film Festival |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2011/08/29/vito-russo-documentary-makes-the-new-york-film-festival/ |website=www.villagevoice.com |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> went on to screen within such festivals as [[Maryland Film Festival]], and made its television debut on [[HBO]] in July, 2012.<ref name=Neil/> The DVD was released by [[First Run Features]] in April, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=DVD Review: 'Vito' |url=https://cine-vue.com/2013/04/dvd-review-vito.html |website=CineVue |accessdate=26 June 2019 |date=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* Phyllis Antonellis as Herself - Vito's cousin\n* Richard Barrios as Himself - Author (\"Screened Out: Playing Gay in Hollywood from Edison to Stonewall\")\n* [[Edmund Bergler]] as Himself - Psychoanalyst, writer ([[archive footage]]) (billed  as Edmund Bergler M.D.)\n* [[Richard Berkowitz]] as Himself - Author\n* Lenny Bloom as Himself - Friend & Lawyer (billed as Leonard Bloom)\n* [[Jay Blotcher]] as Himself - Journalist, writer, publicist, film producer, and activist\n* [[Malcolm Boyd]] as Himself (billed as Reverend Malcolm Boyd)\n* Joseph Brewer as Himself\n* [[Lee Brewster]] as Himself - [[Queens Liberation Front]] (archive footage)\n* [[Tom Brokaw]] as Himself - Journalist (archive footage)\n* [[Marcus Conant|Marcus A. Conant]] as Himself - Doctor and dermatologist (archive footage)\n* [[Stephen Boyd]] as (archive footage) Messala\n* [[Billie Burke]] as (archive footage) [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glinda]]\n* [[George Bancroft (actor)|George Bancroft]] as (archive footage) Bill Bailey\n* [[Jane Darwell]] as (archive footage) Mrs. Winchell - Jack's Mother\n* [[Marcia Pally]] as Herself\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://vitorussomovie.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|1444284|Vito}}\n*{{Rotten-tomatoes|vito|Vito}}\n\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about LGBT film]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the cinema of the United States]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jeffrey Schwarz]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bryan Singer]]\n\n{{bio-documentary-film-stub}}\n{{LGBT-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name    