sc=The [[Siebel ferry]] foundered in a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] between [[Sicily]] and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2.dk/articles/flot.htm|title=Luftwaffe-Fahrenflotillen|publisher=WW2.dk |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tosei Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The fleet supply ship was torpedoed and sunk {{convert|5|nmi|km}} south of [[Tori-shima (Izu Islands)|Tori Shima]] ({{coord|30|14|N|139|45|E}}) by {{USS|Pollack|SS-180|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). One passenger was killed.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/AkikawaO_t.htm |title=Japanese Type 1K Ore Carriers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Toyo Maru|Kawasaku, 1937|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean by {{USS|Haddock|SS-231|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 April==\n''For the foundering of the British cargo ship ''Nagara'' on this day, see the entry for [[List of shipwrecks in March 1943#29 March|29 March 1943]].''\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Altair|1941|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The supply ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sun off [[Kristiansund]], Norway by aircraft of [[Coastal Command]], [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194304/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5615214|shipname=Altair |accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Koa Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the [[Jaluit Atoll]], [[Marshall Islands]] ({{coord|13|11|N|161|57|E}}) by {{USS|Porpoise|SS-172|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Porpoise>{{cite DANFS |title=Nautilus |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss172.txt |accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=NorPQ>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleetpq.html |title=Norwegian Merchant Fleet 1939 \u2013 1945, Ships beginning with P & Q |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Patria|1901|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk off [[Stavanger]], Norway by aircraft of Coastal Command.<ref name=seekrieg194304/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1113513|shipname=Patria |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rygja|1920|2}}\n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[North Sea]] off [[Skagen]], Denmark with the loss of a crew member.<ref name=HomeR>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsr.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet \u2013 WW II, Ships starting with R |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Uragio Maru''\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=U.S. aircraft sank the 3,110-ton [[cargo ship]] in [[Kiska Harbor]] on [[Kiska Island]] in the [[Aleutian Islands]]. ''Uragio Maru'' had not been seaworthy since she suffered damage in an U.S. air attack on Kiska on 31 December 1942 and in a violent storm that struck Kiska on 4 January 1943.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksu>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-u/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (U)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1252||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' collided with {{ship|German flak ship|FlJ 27 Schiewenhorst||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) and sank in the North Sea off [[Borkum]].<ref name=seekrieg194304/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Aloe||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] {{convert|420|nmi|km}} south east of [[Durban]], South Africa ({{coord|32|37|S|37|50|E}}) by {{GS|U-182||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 47 crew survived. The captain was taken on board ''U-182'' as a [[prisoner of war]]. The rest of the crew were rescued by {{SS|Alexander Ramsey||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).<ref name=Aloe>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2846.html |title=Aloe |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Blitar||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The cargo ship romped ahead of the convoy. She was shelled and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] by {{GS|U-229||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). The next day, she was torpedoed and sunk ({{coord|57|45|N|27|30|W}}) by {{GS|U-632||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 26 of her 62 crew.<ref name=Blitar>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2852.html |title=Blitar |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|British Ardour||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean west of Ireland ({{coord|58|08|N|34|04|W}}) by {{GS|U-706||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 62 crew were rescued by {{HMS|Snowflake|K211|6}} and {{HMS|Vidette|D48|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}), the former of which scuttled the ship.<ref name=BA>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2848.html |title=British Ardour |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet patrol boat|No. 095||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=The [[MO-class small guard ship#MO-4 type|''MO-4''-class]] [[patrol vessel]]  was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cf_mo4.htm |title=MO-class small guard ship, USSR |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Jsub|Ro-34||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Kaich\u016b type submarine|Kaich\u016b VI (''Ro-33''-class) submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the [[Russell Islands]] ({{coord|8|15|S|158|58|E}}) by {{USS|O'Bannon|DD-450|6}} and {{USS|Strong|DD-467|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all 66 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|San Isidro||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Spain|1938}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by {{ship|Greek submarine|Katsonis|Y-1|2}} ({{navy|Kingdom of Greece}}).<ref name=seekrieg194304/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Shillong||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean south east of [[Cape Farewell, Greenland]] by {{GS|U-635||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was the torpedoed and sunk ({{coord|57|10|N|35|30|W}}) by {{GS|U-630||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 71 of her 78 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Zamalek||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=Shillong>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2847.html |title=Shillong |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Sunoil||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The tanker straggled behind the convoy. She was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean by {{GS|U-563||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was later torpedoed and sunk at {{coord|58|16|N|34|14|W}} by {{GS|U-530||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 69 crew.<ref name=Sunoil>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2849.html |title=Sunoil |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-167|1942|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40 submarine]] was depth charged and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off the [[Canary Islands]], Spain (approximately {{coord|27|47|N|15|00|W}}) by a [[Lockheed Hudson]] aircraft of [[No. 233 Squadron RAF|233 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]]. She was scuttled the next day. All 52 crew survived.<ref name=U167>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u167.htm |title=U-167 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-635||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean south east of Iceland ({{coord|58|20|N|31|52|W}}) by a [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft of [[No. 120 Squadron RAF|120 Squadron]], Royal Air Force with the loss of all 47 crew.<ref name=U635>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u635.htm |title=U-635 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Vaalaren||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Sweden}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The cargo ship romped ahead of the convoy. She was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean (approximately {{coord|58|N|34|W}}) by {{GS|U-229||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 38 crew.<ref name=Vaalaren>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2845.html |title=Vaalaren |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=10 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Waroonga||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean by {{GS|U-635||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was then torpedoed and damaged further by {{GS|U-630||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 19 of the 132 people aboard. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Joel R. Poinsett||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}) and {{HMS|Loosestrife|K105|6}} ({{navy|UK}}), which scuttled the ship.<ref name=Waroonga>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2851.html |title=Waroonga |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian trawler|Carridi||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[naval trawler]] was sunk at [[Trapani]], [[Sicily]] by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1510&tridit=lodenice&zobraz=A |title=Italy Trawlers Ruzne |publisher=Warshipsww2 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006083326/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=1510&tridit=lodenice&zobraz=A# |archive-date=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|John Sevier||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy GTMO 83]]: The [[Liberty ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Caribbean Sea]] {{convert|20|nmi|km}} off [[Great Inagua Island]], Cuba ({{coord|20|17|N|73|32|W}}) by {{GS|U-185||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 57 crew were rescued by {{USS|Bennett|DD-473|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=LibJo/><ref name=JS>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2853.html |title=John Sevier |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Josephina Thord\u00e9n||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank in the [[Thames Estuary]] ({{coord|51|47|18|N|1|28|42|E}}) with the loss of fifteen of her 55 crew.<ref name=Jordan454>{{cite book |title=The world's merchant fleets, 1939 |first=Roger |last=Jordan |publisher=Chatham publishing |location=London |year=1999 |page=454 