nited Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|6|40|N|13|17|W}}) by {{GS|U-123|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 49 crew were rescued by {{Ship|HMMMS|107}} ({{navy|UK}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fort Rampart||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 233]]: The [[Fort ship]] straggled behind the convoy. She was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|47|22|N|21|58|W}}) by {{GS|U-628||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). She was later torpedoed again by ''U-628'' and then torpedoed, shelled and sunk {{convert|900|nmi|km}} east north east of the [[Azores]], Portugal ({{coord|47|28|N|22|00|W}}) by {{GS|U-226||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of six of her 56 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMCS|Arvida|K113|6}} ({{navy|Canada|1911}}).<ref name=FR>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2868.html |title=Fort Rampart |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|H\u00f8egh Carrier|1935|2}}\n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Den Helder]], Netherlands by [[Bristol Beaufighter]] aircraft of the Royal Air Force with the loss of two of her crew.<ref name=seekrieg194304/><ref name=HomeHe>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsh2.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet \u2013 WW II, Ships starting with He through H\u00f8 |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Liv||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk at [[Porto Torres]], [[Sardinia]] by Royal Air Force aircraft. She was later refloated.<ref name=Liv>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/liv.html |title=D/S Liv |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Manaar||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Indian Ocean south of [[Mauritius]] by {{ship|Italian submarine|Leonardo da Vinci|1939|2}} ({{navy|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}).<ref name=seekrieg194304/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|Japanese transport|Nisshun Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The ammunition transport was torpedoed and sunk {{convert|200|nmi|km}} north north west of Mussau Island, [[Bismarck Archipelago]] ({{coord|01|55|N|148|24|E}}) by {{USS|Drum|SS-228|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). 35 crewmen killed. Survivors rescued by {{Ship|Japanese submarine chaser|CH-18||2}} ({{navy|Empire of Japan}}).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/CH-18_t.htm |title=Japanese Subchasers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|P615}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Oru\u00e7 Reis|submarine}} was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|6|49|N|13|09|W}}) by {{GS|U-123|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 43 crew.<ref name=NH43/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Regent|N41|6}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Rainbow|submarine}} struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Strait of Otranto]] with the loss of all 63 crew.<ref name=NH43/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 2205 Le Jacques Coeur||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] north north west of [[Isola di Femmine]], Sicily, ({{coord|38|15|N|13|13|E}}) by {{HMS|Unseen|P51|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). Four crewmen killed. Survivors rescued by {{ship|Italian submarine chaser|VAS 207||2}} and {{ship|Italian submarine chaser|VAS 230||2}} (both {{navy|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}).<ref name=seekrieg194304/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Russian seiner|Unknown||2}} and {{ship|Russian seiner|Unknown||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Fishing vessel|seiners]] were sunk in the Black Sea by German R boats and S boats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53917&sid=6447e85e3ab126d0f28fae62df794abf |title=Soviet Naval Battles-Black Sea |publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1409 Limburgia||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Seine Bay]] by {{ship|HMMGB|38}} and {{ship|HMMGB|39}} (both {{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194304/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YC-891}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The unpowered covered [[Lighter (barge)|lighter]] sank while under tow off [[Key West, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1943.html |title=Official Chronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==19 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=19 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian destroyer|Alpino|1938|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Soldati|destroyer|2}} was sunk at [[La Spezia]] by British aircraft of the Bomber Command. 48 crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=282 |title=Italy Destroyer Folgore Class |publisher=WarshipsWW2 |accessdate=19 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224045039/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=282 |archive-date=24 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com/2014/01/alpino.html |title=Alpino |publisher=conlapelleappesaaunchiodo.blogspot.com |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list