r |author2=Gerhard H\u00fcmmelchen  |work=W\u00fcrttembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |publisher= |language=German }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[Yugoslav destroyer Ljubljana|''Lubiana'']]\n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Beograd|destroyer}} was either sunk by [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft off Tunisia, or ran aground off [[Cap Bon]], [[French Tunisia|Tunisia]].\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|HMS MTB|63}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The {{sclass2-|Vosper 70'|motor torpedo boat}} was sunk in a collision off [[Benghazi]], [[Libya]], ({{coord|30|50|N|19|50|E}}) with {{Ship|HMS MTB|64}} ({{navy|UK}}). All the crew were rescued.<ref name=ADM19430401>{{cite web |url=https://www.fold3.com/image/301333963 |title=British Admiraly War Diary, 1 April 1943 |publisher=www.fold3.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/16748.html |title=HMS MTB 63 (MTB 63) |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|HMS MTB|64|}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The {{sclass2-|Vosper 70'|motor torpedo boat}} was heavily damaged in a collision off [[Benghazi]], [[Libya]], with {{Ship|HMS MTB|63}} ({{navy|UK}}). One crew member was lost. She reached Benghazi two days later but was not repaired.<ref name=ADM19430401/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/16749.html |title=HMS MTB 64 (MTB 64) |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=RNCas194304>{{cite web |url=https://www.naval-history.net/xDKCas1943-04APR.htm |title=Royal Navy casualties, April 1943 |publisher=www.naval-history.net |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nuoro||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Mediterranean Sea by British aircraft.<ref name=seekrieg194304/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet cargo ship|Uzbekistan||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was wrecked on the north west coast of the United States.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5614848|shipname=Uzbekistan |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YP-235}}\n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=The [[Yard patrol boat|yard patrol craft]] was sunk by an explosion in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1943.html |title=Official Chronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=1 April 2013}}\n</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|City of Baroda||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy NC 9]]: The passenger ship was [[torpedo]]ed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|90|nmi|km}} south west of [[Luderitz Bay]], [[South-West Africa]] ({{coord|27|56|S|15|21|E}}) by {{GS|U-509||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of eight of the 338 people on board. Survivors abandoned ship and were rescued by {{HMT|Cape Warwick|FY167|6}} ({{navy|UK}}). ''City of Baroda'' came ashore two days later and broke up on 26 April. She was declared a total loss.<ref name=CoB>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2840.html |title=City of Baroda |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Dundrum Castle||2}}\n|flag={{Flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=The [[cargo ship]] caught fire and sank in the [[Red Sea]] in the Straits of Perim ({{coord|14|37|N|42|23|E}}). All the crew were saved.<ref name=StanA>{{cite web |url= http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/WWIStandardShipsA-K.htm#A |title=WWI Standard Built Ships A-K |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=ADM19430402>{{cite web |url=https://www.fold3.com/image/301334206 |title=British Admiraly War Diary, 2 April 1943 |publisher=www.fold3.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gogra||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy OS 45]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|230|nmi|km}} west of [[Oporto]], Portugal by {{GS|U-124|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 82 of her 90 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Danby||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and {{SS|New Northland||2}} ({{flag|Canada|1921}}).<ref name=Gogra>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2839.html |title=Gogra |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMIS|Haideri}}\n|flag={{navy|British India}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary patrol vessel was wrecked between [[Madras]], India and [[Trincomallee]], Ceylon while towing six barges.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/22367.html |title=auxiliary patrol vessel Haideri |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Katha||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy OS 45]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|320|nmi|km}} west of Oporto by {{GS|U-124|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of six of her 64 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Danby||2}} ({{Flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and {{HMS|La Malouine|K46|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=Katha>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2838.html |title=Katha |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Lysefjord||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|23|09|N|83|24|W}}) by {{GS|U-155|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of four of her 23 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Howard|1895|2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).<ref name=Lysefjord>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/lysefjord.html |title=D/S Lysefjord |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=LysefjordU155>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2837.html |title=Lysefjord |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|MTB 267||2}}\n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=The [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] 70' [[motor torpedo boat]] was damaged by a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] ({{coord|34|26|N|16|14|E}}) while sailing from [[Benghazi]], [[Italian Libya|Libya]] to [[Malta]] and was scuttled after all the crew were rescued.<ref name=ADM19430402/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/14082.html |title=HMS MTB 267 (MTB 267) |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Melbourne Star|1936|2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|28|05|N|57|30|W}}) by {{GS|U-129|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 115 of the 119 people on board. Survivors were rescued by a [[Consolidated PBY Catalina]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]].<ref name=MS>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2841.html |title=Melbourne Star |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Simon Duhamel II''\n|flag={{flag|Free France}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy TE 20]]: The trawler straggled behind the convoy due to engine trouble. She was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] ({{coord|36|01|N|2|29|W}}) by {{GS|U-755||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 53 of her 54 crew.<ref name=SDII>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2836.html |title=Simon Duhamell II |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Toyo Maru No.2||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''Toyo Maru''-class cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] 5 miles west of Poluwat Island, [[Caroline Islands]] ({{coord|07|22|N|149|18|E}}) by {{USS|Tunny|SS-282|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Fifty-one passengers and crew were killed; there was one survivor.<ref name=Tunny>{{cite DANFS |title=Tunny |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss282.txt |accessdate=4 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-124|1940|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXB submarine]] was shelled and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean west of [[Oporto]], Portugal by {{HMS|Black Swan|L57|6}} and {{HMS|Stonecrop|K142|6}} (both {{Navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 53 crew. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=3 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|Japanese tanker|Arima Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The [[fleet oiler]] was [[torpedo]]ed and damaged north of [[Palau]] ({{coord|10|12|N|134|35|E}}) by {{USS|Haddock|SS-231|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). She sank the next day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/Arima_t.htm |title=Japanese Oilers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gulfstate||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|50|nmi|km}} south east of [[Marathon Key, Florida]] by {{GS|U-155|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 43 of her 61 crew. Survivors discovered by a United States Navy [[blimp]] were rescued by a [[United States Coast Guard]] aircraft with the assistance of {{USS|Noa|DD-343|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Gulfstate>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2842.html |title=Gulfstate |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> 70 years later in 2013, she again became a target, this time of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]'s Remediation of Underwater Legacy Environmental Threats (RULET) project, which hunts down potential sources of oil pollution from sunken vessels.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= https://www.motherjones.com/blue-marble/2013/05/shipwrecks-world-war-ii-oil-leak-uboat\n|title= How Hitler's U-Boats Are Still Attacking Us\n|accessdate= May 21, 2013\n|author= Julia Whitty\n|date= May 21, 2013\n|work= Blue Marble\n|publisher= [[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]\n|quote= The vessel ranked worst on the NOAA's risk assessment scale is the WWII tanker the ''Gulfstate'', torpedoed and sunk off the Florida Keys in 1943.\n}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese submarine chaser|CH-13||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine chaser]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] east of [[Honshu]] ({{coord|41|03|N|141|58|E}}) by {{USS|Pickerel|SS-177|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all hands.<ref name=Pickerel>{{cite DANFS |title=Pickerel |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss177.txt |accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/CH-13_t.htm |title=Japanese Sub Chasers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{Ship|Japanese transport|Florida Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The transport was bombed and sunk at [[Kavieng]], [[New Ireland (island)|New Ireland]] ({{coord|02|35|S|150|49|E}}) by [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] aircraft of the United States [[Fifth Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/TenryuM_t.htm |title=Japanese Transports |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/USN-Chron/USN-Chron-1943.html |title=Official Chronology of the US Navy in WWII |publisher=Ibiblio |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 78||2}}  \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 104||2}}  \n|flag={{luftwaffe|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] foundered in a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] between [[Sicily]] and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2.dk/articles/flot.htm|title=Luftwaffe-Fahrenflotillen|publisher=WW2.dk |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 196||2}}  \n|flag={{luftwaffe|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] foundered in a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] between [[Sicily]] and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2.dk/articles/flot.htm|title=Luftwaffe-Fahrenflotillen|publisher=WW2.dk |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 203||2}}  \n|flag={{luftwaffe|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] foundered in a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] between [[Sicily]] and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2.dk/articles/flot.htm|title=Luftwaffe-Fahrenflotillen|publisher=WW2.dk |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German siebel ferry|SF 223||2}}  \n|flag={{luftwaffe|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The [[Siebel ferry]] foundered in a storm in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] between [[Sicily]] and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_sf40.htm |title=Siebelfahre 40 and Siebelfahre 41, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ww2.dk/articles/flot.htm|title=Luftwaffe-Fahrenflotillen|publisher=WW2.dk |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tosei Maru||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The fleet supply ship was torpedoed and sunk {{convert|5|nmi|km}} south of [[Tori-shima (Izu Islands)|Tori Shima]] ({{coord|30|14|N|139|45|E}}) by {{USS|Pollack|SS-180|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). One passenger was killed.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.combinedfleet.com/AkikawaO_t.htm |title=Japanese Type 1K Ore Carriers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Toyo Maru|Kawasaku, 1937|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean by {{USS|Haddock|SS-231|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 April==\n''For the foundering of the British cargo ship ''Nagara'' on this day, see the entry for [[List of shipwrecks in March 1943#29 March|29 March 1943]].''\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Altair|1941|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The supply ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sun off [[Kristiansund]], Norway by aircraft of [[Coastal Command]], [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194304/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5615214|shipname=Altair |accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Koa Maru||2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off the [[Jaluit Atoll]], [[Marshall Islands]] ({{coord|13|11|N|161|57|E}}) by {{USS|Porpoise|SS-172|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Porpoise>{{cite DANFS |title=Nautilus |url= http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss172.txt |accessdate=29 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=NorPQ>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleetpq.html |title=Norwegian Merchant Fleet 1939 \u2013 1945, Ships beginning with P & Q |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Patria|1901|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk off [[Stavanger]], Norway by aircraft of Coastal Command.<ref name=seekrieg194304/><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1113513|shipname=Patria |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rygja|1920|2}}\n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[North Sea]] off [[Skagen]], Denmark with the loss of a crew member.<ref name=HomeR>{{cite web |url= http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsr.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet \u2013 WW II, Ships starting with R |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Uragio Maru''\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=U.S. aircraft sank the 3,110-ton [[cargo ship]] in [[Kiska Harbor]] on [[Kiska Island]] in the [[Aleutian Islands]]. ''Uragio Maru'' had not been seaworthy since she suffered damage in an U.S. air attack on Kiska on 31 December 1942 and in a violent storm that struck Kiska on 4 January 1943.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksu>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-u/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (U)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German trawler|V 1252||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' collided with {{ship|German flak ship|FlJ 27 Schiewenhorst||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) and sank in the North Sea off [[Borkum]].<ref name=seekrieg194304/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 April 1943 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Aloe||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] {{convert|420|nmi|km}} south east of [[Durban]], South Africa ({{coord|32|37|S|37|50|E}}) by {{GS|U-182||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 47 crew survived. The captain was taken on board ''U-182'' as a [[prisoner of war]]. The rest of the crew were rescued by {{SS|Alexander Ramsey||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).<ref name=Aloe>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2846.html |title=Aloe |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Blitar||2}}\n|flag={{flag|Netherlands}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The cargo ship romped ahead of the convoy. She was shelled and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] by {{GS|U-229||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). The next day, she was torpedoed and sunk ({{coord|57|45|N|27|30|W}}) by {{GS|U-632||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 26 of her 62 crew.<ref name=Blitar>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2852.html |title=Blitar |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|British Ardour||2}}\n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 231]]: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean west of Ireland ({{coord|58|08|N|34|04|W}}) by {{GS|U-706||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 62 crew were rescued by {{HMS|Snowflake|K211|6}} and {{HMS|Vidette|D48|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}), the former of which scuttled the ship.<ref name=BA>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2848.html |title=British Ardour |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet patrol boat|No. 095||2}}\n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union}}\n|desc=The [[MO-class small guard ship#MO-4 type|''MO-4''-cla