{"title_page": "Edwin Keith Thomson", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=Edwin Keith Thomson\n| image name=Edwin Keith Thompson (Wyoming Congressman).jpg\n| office = [[United States Senator]]<br /> from [[Wyoming]]\n| term_start= ''January 3, 1961 (Scheduled)''\n| term_end  = ''Died before term began''\n| predecessor = [[Joseph C. O'Mahoney]]\n| successor   = [[John J. Hickey]]\n| state1 = [[Wyoming]]\n| district1 = [[Wyoming's At-large congressional district|At-large]]\n| term_start1 = January 3, 1955\n| term_end1 = December 9, 1960\n| preceded1 = [[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William Henry Harrison]]\n| succeeded1 =[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William Henry Harrison]]\n| office2 = Member of the [[Wyoming House of Representatives]]\n| term2 = 1952\u20131954\n| birth_date={{birth date|1919|2|08}}\n| birth_place=[[Newcastle, Wyoming|Newcastle]], [[Wyoming]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1960|12|09|1919|2|08}}\n| death_place=[[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]], [[Wyoming]]\n| death_cause=[[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]]\n| resting_place=[[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| party     = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse= [[Thyra Thomson]]\n| children=Three sons\n| religion=\n| occupation= Attorney/Lawmaker \n| residence= [[Cheyenne, Wyoming|Cheyenne]], Wyoming\n| alma_mater=[[University of Wyoming]]\n| signature = \n| branch=[[United States Army]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n|rank=[[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|serviceyears=1941 - 1946\n}}\n'''Edwin Keith Thomson''' (February 8, 1919 \u2013 December 9, 1960), usually known as Keith Thomson, was a [[United States Representative]] from [[Wyoming]]. A highly decorated [[World War II]] veteran, Thomson served three terms in Wyoming's only U.S. House seat. On November 8, 1960, he was elected to the U.S. Senate, but died a month later of a heart attack before taking office.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Newcastle, Wyoming|Newcastle]], Wyoming, he grew up on a ranch in [[Crook County, Wyoming|Crook County]] and attended public schools in [[Beulah, Wyoming|Beulah]], Wyoming, and [[Spearfish, South Dakota|Spearfish]], [[South Dakota]]. He graduated in 1941 from the [[University of Wyoming]] Law School in [[Laramie, Wyoming|Laramie]]. While in law school he met his wife, [[Thyra Thomson|Thyra Godfrey Thomson]], and they were married in 1939.<ref>\"Former Sec. of State Thyra Thomson dies,\" ''Billings Gazette'' (Wyoming), John Barron, June 12, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nThomson was called to [[active duty]] on March 24, 1941 and commanded the Second Battalion, Three Hundred and Sixty-second Infantry Regiment, Ninety-first Division. He was released from active duty as a lieutenant colonel on January 24, 1946. He had been admitted to the [[bar (law)|bar]] in 1941 and commenced the practice of law in [[Cheyenne, Wyoming|Cheyenne]] in February 1946; he was a delegate to the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] in [[Chicago]] and was a member of the [[Wyoming House of Representatives]] from 1952 to 1954.\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:ANCExplorer Thyra Thomson grave.jpg|thumb|left|Grave at Arlington National Cemetery]]\nThomson was elected as a member of the [[USRepublican|Republican]] party to the [[84th Congress|Eighty-fourth]], [[85th Congress|Eighty-fifth]], and [[86th Congress|Eighty-sixth]] Congresses and served from January 3, 1955, until his death.  He did not seek renomination to the Eighty-seventh Congress, but was elected to the [[United States Senate]] on November 8, 1960, for the term commencing January 3, 1961. However, he died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] in [[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]], Wyoming in December, before his term in the Senate began. Democratic Governor [[John J. Hickey]] appointed himself to the seat but was defeated in a 1962 special election to serve out the term by Republican [[Milward L. Simpson]]. Thomson was interred at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].\n\nFollowing Thomson's death, his wife [[Thyra Thomson]] was elected in 1962 as [[Wyoming Secretary of State]]. She was re-elected to five more terms, and served in that office for twenty-four years, until 1987.<ref>Mark Junge, \"The Wind is My Witness: A Wyoming Album\", Roberts Rinehart, 1997.</ref><ref>\"Former Sec. of State Thyra Thomson dies,\" ''Billings Gazette'', June 12, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://kgab.com/former-secretary-of-state-thyra-thomson-dies/ Obituary]</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Wyoming\n|district = AL\n|before=[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William H. Harrison]]\n|years=January 3, 1955{{spaced ndash}}December 9, 1960\n|after=[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William H. Harrison]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Law|Politics|Conservatism|World War II}}\n* [[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1950\u201399)]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|T000229}}\n*{{Findagrave|7567}}\n* The [https://rmoa.unm.edu/docviewer.php?docId=wyu-ah09904.xml Edwin Keith Thomson papers] at the [http://www.uwyo.edu/ahc/ American Heritage Center]\n\n{{Wyoming Representatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, Edwin}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wyoming House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:People from Crook County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrence County, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:University of Wyoming College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Wyoming lawyers]]\n[[Category:Wyoming Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=Edwin Keith Thomson\n| image name=Edwin Keith Thompson (Wyoming Congressman).jpg\n| office = [[United States Senator]]<br /> from [[Wyoming]]\n| term_start= ''January 3, 1961 (Scheduled)''\n| term_end  = ''Died before term began''\n| predecessor = [[Joseph C. O'Mahoney]]\n| successor   = [[John J. Hickey]]\n| state1 = [[Wyoming]]\n| district1 = [[Wyoming's At-large congressional district|At-large]]\n| term_start1 = January 3, 1955\n| term_end1 = December 9, 1960\n| preceded1 = [[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William Henry Harrison]]\n| succeeded1 =[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William Henry Harrison]]\n| office2 = Member of the [[Wyoming House of Representatives]]\n| term2 = 1952\u20131954\n| birth_date={{birth date|1919|2|08}}\n| birth_place=[[Newcastle, Wyoming|Newcastle]], [[Wyoming]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1960|12|09|1919|2|08}}\n| death_place=[[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]], [[Wyoming]]\n| death_cause=[[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]]\n| resting_place=[[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| party     = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse= [[Thyra Thomson]]\n| children=Three sons\n| religion=\n| occupation= Attorney/Lawmaker \n| residence= [[Cheyenne, Wyoming|Cheyenne]], Wyoming\n| alma_mater=[[University of Wyoming]]\n| signature = \n| branch=[[United States Army]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n|rank=[[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|serviceyears=1941 - 1946\n}}\n'''Edwin Keith Thomson''' (February 8, 1919 \u2013 December 9, 1960), usually known as Keith Thomson, was a [[United States Representative]] from [[Wyoming]]. A highly decorated [[World War II]] veteran, Thomson served three terms in Wyoming's only U.S. House seat. On November 8, 1960, he was elected to the U.S. Senate, but died a month later of a heart attack before taking office.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Newcastle, Wyoming|Newcastle]], Wyoming, he grew up on a ranch in [[Crook County, Wyoming|Crook County]] and attended public schools in [[Beulah, Wyoming|Beulah]], Wyoming, and [[Spearfish, South Dakota|Spearfish]], [[South Dakota]]. He graduated in 1941 from the [[University of Wyoming]] Law School in [[Laramie, Wyoming|Laramie]]. While in law school he met his wife, [[Thyra Thomson|Thyra Godfrey Thomson]], and they were married in 1939.<ref>\"Former Sec. of State Thyra Thomson dies,\" ''Billings Gazette'' (Wyoming), John Barron, June 12, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nThomson was called to [[active duty]] on March 24, 1941 and commanded the Second Battalion, Three Hundred and Sixty-second Infantry Regiment, Ninety-first Division. He was released from active duty as a lieutenant colonel on January 24, 1946. He had been admitted to the [[bar (law)|bar]] in 1941 and commenced the practice of law in [[Cheyenne, Wyoming|Cheyenne]] in February 1946; he was a delegate to the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] in [[Chicago]] and was a member of the [[Wyoming House of Representatives]] from 1952 to 1954.\n\n==Political career==\n\n[[File:ANCExplorer Thyra Thomson grave.jpg|thumb|left|Grave at Arlington National Cemetery]]\nThomson was elected as a member of the [[USRepublican|Republican]] party to the [[84th Congress|Eighty-fourth]], [[85th Congress|Eighty-fifth]], and [[86th Congress|Eighty-sixth]] Congresses and served from January 3, 1955, until his death.  He did not seek renomination to the Eighty-seventh Congress, but was elected to the [[United States Senate]] on November 8, 1960, for the term commencing January 3, 1961. However, he died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] in [[Cody, Wyoming|Cody]], Wyoming in December, before his term in the Senate began. Democratic Governor [[John J. Hickey]] appointed himself to the seat but was defeated in a 1962 special election to serve out the term by Republican [[Milward L. Simpson]]. Thomson was interred at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].\n\nFollowing Thomson's death, his wife [[Thyra Thomson]] was elected in 1962 as [[Wyoming Secretary of State]]. She was re-elected to five more terms, and served in that office for twenty-four years, until 1987.<ref>Mark Junge, \"The Wind is My Witness: A Wyoming Album\", Roberts Rinehart, 1997.</ref><ref>\"Former Sec. of State Thyra Thomson dies,\" ''Billings Gazette'', June 12, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://kgab.com/former-secretary-of-state-thyra-thomson-dies/ Obituary]</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Wyoming\n|district = AL\n|before=[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William H. Harrison]]\n|years=January 3, 1955{{spaced ndash}}December 9, 1960\n|after=[[William H. Harrison (Wyoming Congressman)|William H. Harrison]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Law|Politics|Conservatism|World War II}}\n* [[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1950\u201399)]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|T000229}}\n*{{Findagrave|7567}}\n* The [https://rmoa.unm.edu/docviewer.php?docId=wyu-ah09904.xml Edwin Keith Thomson papers] at the [http://www.uwyo.edu/ahc/ American Heritage Center]\n\n{{Wyoming Representatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, Edwin}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wyoming House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:People from Crook County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrence County, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:University of Wyoming College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Wyoming lawyers]]\n[[Category:Wyoming Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "WFinch", "label": "safe", "comme